{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8cc793ff-fc9a-450e-8dfc-5d5eaf0cf7b1","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Typical transition order:**\n\n| Scenario | Events |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| Switch away | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| Switch back | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| Close app | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |\n| iOS background | `Deactivated → Stopped → Backgrounding` |\n\n> `Backgrounding` is **iOS-only** — use it to save state before the OS may terminate your app. All other events fire on every platform.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e0dc0c5f-3eac-4958-849a-40635f3b42a4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI — I can answer it directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":431,"requestId":"142B:29F7F6:6A1B2FB:7270C25:6A03CCBA"},"id":"c37ead46-8524-46fc-acc4-8859b04ad3f6","timestamp":"2026-05-13T00:58:42.017Z","parentId":"09a38d99-8d1d-49b4-94cb-412047dcba4a"}
